# CLAUDE.md.example

> A `CLAUDE.md` is like a toothbrush: useful daily, but don't use someone
> else's. This is a starting point, not a config to copy wholesale. Take it to
> your project (or `~/.claude/`) root, throw out what doesn't fit *your* mouth,
> and fill in the `<placeholders>` with your own habits.
>
> **First line must be `# <Project Name>`** — Claude Code and many skills read it
> to identify the project. (This file uses `# CLAUDE.md.example` as its own title;
> replace it.)
>
> Sections marked **[core]** are near-universal — keep them. Sections marked
> **[pattern]** showcase a technique; adopt if it fits. `<!-- example: ... -->`
> blocks show the *shape* of a personal rule so you can write your own — they are
> not defaults.
>
> **Design principle — keep this file lean.** It loads on *every* turn (hard limit
> ~4k chars/file). So it holds only *triggers + standing biases*; bulky lookup
> detail lives in on-demand files under `.claude/rules/` that a one-line pointer
> tells Claude to read *when* it's needed. Each section below follows that split.

## Security 🔒 [core]

Never read/parse files holding secrets (keys, tokens, credentials, `.env`, certs).
Non-obvious ones too: `.npmrc`, `.pypirc`, cloud service-key JSON. If asked →
warn + require explicit confirmation.

## Communication [core]

- Clarify before big tasks; never hallucinate; say "I don't know" over speculation.

## Execution defaults [core]

Classify the task first, then match the tool — don't start big and walk back, or
start blind and escalate through failure. Genuinely ambiguous/big/novel → top tier
to frame it. When a call is non-trivial, route it deliberately instead of guessing:

- **model / effort** — don't default to your most expensive model. Route by task
  shape (chores → cheapest · single-file plumbing → mid-tier · strategy / hard
  refactor / security audit → top tier · very large context → long-context model).
  Changing *effort* keeps the prompt cache (cheap); switching *model* breaks it
  (costly). If you have a model-selection skill, invoke it here.
- **sub-agents / fan-out** — delegate to isolate context. Sweeping many files where
  only the conclusion matters → fan out to a cheaper model. Independent per-item
  work → parallel sub-agents. Never shard cross-item reasoning or final synthesis
  — those stay on the main thread. If you have an execution-topology skill, invoke
  it here.

<!-- The two bullets above name *capabilities*, not skill slugs, so this file
     stays portable. If your routing detail is bulky, move the table into a skill
     (its description auto-fires) or a .claude/rules/ file, and keep only the
     trigger here. -->

## Planning [core]

- **Boulder → Pebbles**: boulders (multi-step, architectural, or ambiguous) get
  planned into trackable stories before work starts; pebbles (single file,
  obvious) just get done.

## Output style [core]

- **Human-facing output** (responses, docs, reports): visual-first. Prefer
  diagrams for flows/decisions/comparisons; structured data as clean YAML/JSON.
- **LLM-facing artifacts** (context files, specs, agent prompts): token-optimized.
  Strip prose, keep directives/facts/structure. No decoration.

## Temp files [core]

- Write throwaway files under a single dedicated scratch dir (e.g. `.tmp/{task}/`),
  never the system `/tmp`. Clean up when done.

## Git [pattern]

> Pick the posture that matches how you work; delete the other example.

